The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Thursday, June 03, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Krishnagar (Nadia), June 2: Police today arrested a girls father and uncle on the charge of murdering her fiance a day before their scheduled wedding a month ago. 				 																																	The body of Rajiv Sarkar was recovered from the Jalangi on May 3. His father Nirmal suspected foul play and lodged a complaint against Niranjan Saha and his brother Prabhat. The siblings were arrested after the post-mortem report said Rajiv was struck with something on his head and then thrown into the river. 				 																																	Calcutta: Italian ambassador Antonio Armellini met chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee and offered to restore Calcuttas heritage buildings. He said his country is already working with the state in the leather and gold jewellery sectors and could collaborate in the agro industry and food-processing sectors. 				 																																	Calcutta: Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will meet the chiefs of 40 municipalities and discuss implementation of a Rs 700-crore DFID project to improve infrastructure in slums and focus on rehabilitation of the poor. 				 																																	Calcutta: The Kali temple at Kalighat here will remain closed from 6 am to 2 pm on Thursday for a special ritual, police said. After 2, devotees will be allowed into the temple and offer puja as usual. 				 																																	Calcutta: A 12-hour bandh was observed at Kulpi in South 24-Parganas on Wednesday in protest against the murder of panchayat pradhan Nurul Haldar, a Congress worker, on Monday. Party leaders claimed police had harassed their supporters during the bandh and said they would block roads in protest on Thursday. 
